Diane,

You may want to use XSL and XSLT... Print out your Junit reports into
and XML format (&lt;format /&gt;) and then use a standalone Java program or
any other tool to transform the XML into excel sheets. I know that it
is not too tough to make comma seperated .csv files from XML/XSL. I am
not too sure what will it take to create the binary .xls files.

as far as &quot;velocity&quot; factor you mentioned, take a look at section
4.3.2 of the book JUnit in Action. That refers to a tool called Clover
- never used it  - but sounds like what you are looking for.

hope this helps.


On Wed, 12 Jan 2005 15:16:09 +0000, didoss@...
&lt;didoss@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; Paul -
&gt; 
&gt; Thanks for the reply.  Unfortunately, we are already doing that.
&gt; 
&gt; We run a nightlybuild with tests.  It copies the previous results to a
&gt; backup-reports directory, cleans the reports directory, and then creates the
&gt; current results html files.  Then, we send out an e-mail to the team, with
&gt; the links to the various reports (for different &#39;chunks&#39; of code), both
&gt; current and previous.
&gt; 
&gt; Every morning, I am opening those reports and copying the highest level data
&gt; (from the summary section -&gt; #tests, #failures, #errors) into an excel
&gt; spreadsheet.
&gt; 
&gt; Currently, we are trying to get our testing back under control - many
&gt; iterations of allowing people to say their stories were complete without
&gt; appropriate - or even working - tests.  Additionally, in the past, we have
&gt; found that we have a velocity treshhold - after which our testing goes
&gt; downhill.  So, we have a need to maintain this historical information, over
&gt; the life of the project.
&gt; 
&gt; I am looking for a way to automate this.  What I&#39;m thinking of is:
&gt; when the reporting functionality totals the summary numbers, it could also
&gt; output to another file type (ideally, straight into an excel spreadsheet;
&gt; minimally, into a file that can be used as a data source for a spreadsheet)
&gt; a configurable data set: date, time, #tests, #failures, #errors, #time.
&gt; 
&gt; Dianne
&gt; 
&gt; -------------- Original message -------------- 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; Dianne Doss asked
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; Is there an automated way to output the summary data (#tests,
&gt; #errors, #failures) from my JUnit Report to an external file
&gt; (possibly xls, or a file accessible by spreadsheet) in order to
&gt; maintain a history of our results?
&gt; 
&gt; In the ideal world, there would never be any errors or failures, but
&gt; the point of the testing is to make us confident in making code
&gt; changes.  We run a nightlybuild regression, so the next morning I
&gt; can see if I missed anything (sometimes the failures are well
&gt; removed from the actual class that was changed).
&gt; 
&gt; So, we would like to be able to record historical data of the
&gt; fluctuations.  In the past, manually, we have found that the
&gt; errors/failures go up when we get above a certain velocity.
&gt; 
&gt; Thanks for any insight that can be provided.
&gt; 
&gt; Dianne Doss
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; Dear Doss,
&gt; 
&gt;               If you are generating JUnit Report through Ant, definitely you
&gt; should write one build.xml file. Before generating new report, why not you
&gt; take copy of the previous report.  In Ant API  contains copy tag and move
&gt; tag. So
&gt; first step you take a back up using Copy/ Move tag.
&gt; Second step you clear your old report using delete tag.
&gt; Third step create report folder again.
&gt; Finally you generate new report.
